5.5 Compare hosting types and recommendation for a blog.
Ans--
Comparison
Shared Hosting: Multiple users share one physical server. It's cheap but offers low performance and less security.

Cloud Hosting: Your site is hosted on a network of virtual servers. It is highly scalable and has high uptime.

Static Hosting: Specifically serves pre-built HTML/CSS files. It is the fastest and most secure for simple sites.

Recommendation for a Personal Blog
For a personal blog, I recommend Static Hosting (using GitHub Pages or Netlify).

Reasons:

Zero Cost: You don't need to pay for a monthly subscription.

Speed: Static files load much faster than dynamic ones.

Maintenance: There is no server to maintain or database to update, making it perfect for a long-term blog.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
5.4 Deploy a static HTML/CSS website using GitHub Pages.
Ans--
Follow these steps to deploy your static site:

Initialize Git: Open your terminal in your project folder and run git init.

Push to GitHub: Create a repository on GitHub, then push your code:
------------------------------------------------------
|            Bash                                      |
|                                                      |
|           git add .                                  |
|           git commit -m "Initial commit"             |
|           git branch -M main                         |
|           git remote add origin <your-repo-url>      |
|           git push -u origin main                    |
|           Enable Pages:                              |
--------------------------------------------------------
Navigate to your repo's Settings tab.

Click Pages in the left sidebar.

Under "Branch," select main and click Save.

View Site: Your site will be live at https://<username>.github.io/<repo-name>/.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
5.3 List and describe three free hosting platforms.
Ans--
1. GitHub Pages

Description: GitHub Pages allows you to host static websites (HTML, CSS, JavaScript) directly from a GitHub repository. It's widely used for personal portfolios, project demos, and documentation.

Pros:

-Free and reliable.
-Supports custom domains.
-Integrated with Git version control.

Limitations:

-Only supports static sites (no server-side code like PHP).
-Limited to GitHubâ€™s bandwidth policies.

2. Netlify

Description: Netlify is a cloud platform that provides free hosting for static websites with continuous deployment from Git repositories. It also offers serverless functions for dynamic features.

Pros:

-Easy to deploy with drag-and-drop or Git integration.
-Built-in SSL, form handling, and serverless functions.
-Automatic site updates with Git commits.

Limitations:

-Free plan has bandwidth and build limits.
-More advanced features require a paid plan.

3. Firebase Hosting (by Google)

Description: Firebase Hosting provides fast and secure hosting for web apps, including static and dynamic content. It integrates well with other Firebase services like authentication and database.

Pros:

-Supports both static and dynamic content.
-Free SSL certificates and global CDN.
-Easy deployment using Firebase CLI.

Limitations:

-Limited free tier usage (bandwidth and storage).
-Requires learning Firebase CLI for deployment.

